<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="518" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,834,1905]" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">
Description as for 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Girard" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[359,478,835,861]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cottidae" genus="Cottus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gulosus">
<emphasis box="[359,478,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">C. gulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Meristics of sculpins used in this study (
<tableCitation box="[943,1028,835,861]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[150,238,542,568]" captionTargetBox="[165,1966,655,1605]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Meristic values for Riffle Sculpin samples from the UC Davis Museum of Wildlife and Fish and the California Academy of Sciences, San Francisco. Cottus asper and C.pitensis data is presented for comparison.? means ‘could not be determined’. Locations include the year collected. See Table 2 for more precise location information. Sculpins at locations with * were C. asper originally identified as C. gulosus" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Table 1</tableCitation>
, n = 45): anal-fin rays (12–14), dorsal spines (6–9), dorsal-fin rays (15–19), dorsal fins joined? (variable), black spot present on dorsal, palatine teeth usually present (variable), mouth vs eye (variable but maxilla mostly reaches mid-eye), chin pores (0–2), pelvic fin spines + rays (1+3), pelvics do not touch vent, pectoral-fin rays (14–16), preopercular spines (2), lateral line (complete/incomplete, variable), lateral line pores (25–35). Other characters are listed in 
<tableCitation box="[1090,1174,979,1005]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[150,238,542,568]" captionTargetBox="[165,1966,655,1605]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Meristic values for Riffle Sculpin samples from the UC Davis Museum of Wildlife and Fish and the California Academy of Sciences, San Francisco. Cottus asper and C.pitensis data is presented for comparison.? means ‘could not be determined’. Locations include the year collected. See Table 2 for more precise location information. Sculpins at locations with * were C. asper originally identified as C. gulosus" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
